Value of 3 for "tm.img" Value Type means that the bit size 3=8-bit unsigned integer. Value of 4 for "landcover.tif" Value Type means that the bit size 4=8-bit signed.

In [62]:
import arcpy
from arcpy.sa import *
elev = arcpy.Raster("elevation")
outraster = Slope(elev)
outraster
Out[62]:

The elevation is highlighted by lighter values. Values ranging from 0-68.4449 indicate higher slope by lighter values so that the viewer can easily interpret changes in slope. this gives the viewers an idea that the lighter the value, the more steep/quickly the elevation is changing at this point.

In [64]:
Render (elev, colormap="Elevation #1")
Out[64]:

This rendering of the slope raster makes it easier to see low elevation distinguished from higher elevation. The higher elevation is is shown in darker red==>white, while the lower elevation is shown in the light-teal==>light-tan

In [68]:
from arcpy.sa import *
from arcpy.ia import *
elev_clip = Clip(elev, "watershed_HUC12.shp")

elev_clip.save("elev_clip")
elev_clip
Out[68]:

This is the elevation raster clipped to the extant of the watershed. The relevance of this clipped raster is that the raster no longer will contain data(DEM) beyond the influence of the watershed of interest. When studying ecological effects of the watershed it is critical to limit the data input/output to the area of interest
